**Abstract:**
A major essay dated October 4, 1994, on "Blaise Pascal." The document extensively quotes Pascal's works and develops a critique of the traditional proofs for God's existence. It argues that Pascal's objection to metaphysical proofs is that they yield only a conceptual God incapable of motivating love and adoration, not the God of religious relationship. The author contrasts the primitive man's exposure to the god-Sun with Aquinas's theoretical contemplation, arguing that Aquinas's proofs deal with an abstract datum rather than the concrete world of exposed agents. Develops the distinction between knowing God theoretically (assent) and practically (adoration, prayer).

**AI Recommendation:** Central theoretical essay on Pascal and the critique of natural theology; develops the exposed-subject/contemplator distinction in relation to proofs of God.

